A.1 Performance Comparison Table

Metric 2023 Prototypes 2025 State-of-the-Art Fundamental Physical Limit Notes
Size (μm) 100-500 70-300 Diffusion-limited (~10) Smaller than human cell
Speed (μm/s) 20-50 50-150 Brownian motion ~10 (RMS) ~1 body length/second
Memory (bits) 64 128-512 Landauer's (kT ln2 per bit) Core: ~128 bits
Power Draw (pW) 5-10 8-15 Harvesting limit (light intensity) Requires continuous illumination
Swarm Coordination ~10 units ~100 units Channel capacity (C=5-20 bps) Bottleneck is communication
Sensing Resolution 1.0 °C 0.3-1.0 °C Thermal noise limit Single modality (temperature)
Unit Cost (USD) $0.05-0.10 $0.02-0.05 CMOS scaling + integration premium Projection: $0.003-0.01 by 2030

A.2 Visual Element Guide for Publication

· Fig. 1: System Architecture: Cross-sectional diagram showing integrated layers: Photovoltaics, CMOS logic, and electrochemical actuators.
· Fig. 2: Propulsion Physics: Illustration of induced-charge electro-osmosis flow field around asymmetric electrodes in low-Re regime.
· Fig. 3: Swarm Scaling Limit: Graph plotting effective communication bandwidth per robot vs. swarm size, showing S/N ∝ 1/√N decay.
· Fig. 4: Yield Breakdown: Sankey diagram visualizing the contribution of each process step (Y_CMOS, Y_release, Y_integration, Y_test) to final yield.
· Fig. 5: Physical Scale Comparison: Micro-robot on US penny and SEM images showing integrated components (photovoltaics, electrodes).

A.3 Current Specifications (Consolidated)

· Dimensions: 70×70×5 μm to 300×300×10 μm
· Propulsion: Electrokinetic, 50-150 μm/s in dilute H₂O₂/electrolytes
· Power: 8-15 pW harvested under 50 mW/cm² illumination
· Computation: 8-bit core, 1-10 kHz clock, ~128 bits core memory (up to ~512 bits integrated)
· Sensing: Temperature, 0.3-1.0°C resolution
· Communication: 5-20 bps via motion encoding
· Lifetime: 30-180 days in controlled, illuminated fluid
· Manufacturing Yield: ~30% functional devices per wafer
· Current Cost: $0.02-$0.05 per functional unit (research scale)

